      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") So the LXX. have translated ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "כבוד ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in Hebrew poetry; the signification of which may be gathered from Ps. 30:13, “My glory (i.e. my tongue or my soul) may sing praise,” with which comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the words in antithesis are, dust and glory; just as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “Lay mine honour in the dust;” also, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 57:7-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “My heart is fixed,” etc. “Awake up, my glory; awake up, psaltery and harp” wherein glory stands midway between the heart and the instruments; also, from this very saying, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 16:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", wherein the glory is put midway between the heart and the flesh. Therefore it denotes the very flower of nature, which even especially puts itself forth through the tongue, the voice, or singing; for glory is to the flesh the same that the flower is to the grass or herb; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 1:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “All flesh is as grass, and all the glory of man as the flower of grass:” or the beauty of its look, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jam 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “The sun withereth the grass, and the flower thereof falleth, and the grace (or beauty) of the fashion (or look) of it (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἡ εὐπρέπεια τοῦ προσώπου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") perisheth.”—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔτι δὲ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", moreover indeed) also, so therefore. Epitasis [an emphatic addition to a previous enunciation. Append.].",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
